Notes: Ma(2) Shenwen [24604] Shenwen was the youngest son of Yuehena [24518] and his mingzi deviates from the generational indicators used by all of his elder brothers and probably is a transliteration of a Uighur name. I suspect that the other descendants of Yuehena with non-Chinese names were either sons of Shenwen or the youngest sons of the grandsons of Yuehena. Since all sons of Run [24521] share the same generational names, by this time the completely Sinicized branch of the lineage did not retain what appears to be remnants of the ultimogeniture that characterized the culture of many nomadic peoples including of the Mongols. Xu(4) Guozhen [10024] Author of the medical text Yu yue yuan fang, finished in 1266? (Ding Fubao, 500b-501a). Fled from Jiangzhou at end of Jin and temporarily lived in Taiyuan. In 1253, he accompanied the Mongol army in the Yunnan campaign, in 1259 he accompanied Qubilai's army's investiture of Ezhou and saved many Song people from execution. In 1260, he was appointed Taiyi yuan tidian and in 1266 awarded a golden tiger talley (probably for completing the medical work cited above). In 1275 he was appointed to President of the Board of Rites (Libu shangshu). He died at the age of 76, which suggests that he was born before 1234 and therefore could not have lived past 1309. YS, 168.24b-27b. Du(3) Sijing [10004] The third son of Feng [10001], he began his career as did his brothers as changguan of Weisheng jun, a post his father received as a reward for his surrender to the Mongols in about 1234. Sijing had a far more successful career than his brothers, holding several high posts in the Yuan censorate. He was also the author of the Ji sheng ba cao [fang], 19 ch., and reputed author of several other medical texts. Notices of his writings appear in JS, YWZ, 46a and YS, YWZ, 3.14a. The JS notice identifies the text as completed during the period 1314-1320. The Gest library edition call number is 9100/1035.89. CHECK WDY for prefaces, etc. WDY, 1, 570.

Jia(3) Juzhen [28885] Reconstruction of the history of this lineage was complicated and a CHECK of Juzhen's funerary inscription will hopefully confirm the following: Juzheng's grandfather, Shouqian (or Yiqian) [28886] (q.v.) is identified in JS and Zhao ZZ (1567) as a Wu Zhou (沃州) resident. When Kafeng fell to the Mongols, Juzhen, still a lad, fled from Kaifeng to Huolu county, where he is grouped with the biographies of the famous Song dynasty Hedong Jia(3). Wu Zhou and Zhending Fu are contiguous prefectures and Pingji and Huolu counties are only one county apart. My guess is that Yiqing [28887], Juzhen's father (identified in Umehara as Yi), held office in Kaifeng at the end of Jin. At some time in the past, a member of the Huolu Jia(3) moved the short distance to Pingji, and that Juzhen (or more exact, his mother), returned to the ancestral home. Huolu XZ (1556), pp. 735-738. YS, 153.322-325. WDY, 3, pp. 1634-5.

Wang(2) Xin(4) [28766] There were several judicious guesses involved in piecing together this probable lineage. Xin(4) married Zuo(1) Shi [28767], an Anyang county resident. Hu Zhiyu [28603] was Xin(4)'s son-in-law. Wang(2) Yun(5) [28617] identifies Xin, in a beiyin, as a Nanyan (南燕) person, which is the ancient name for Yidu Xian. Wang(2) Bowen(3) [28769], father of Hu(1) Zhiyu's son-in-law, Wang(2) Xixian [28770], is identified as a Donglu (東魯) or Shandong resident who moved to Zhangde Fu. There are either a strange combination of coincidences or Xin was Bowen's father.

Notes: Shi(5) Changru [29966] The three funerary inscriptions that trace the historiy of this lineage are confusing. Zhu Gui, WJ, 5.109-111, traces the ancestry to Shi(5) Hao and then records a one move from Ningbo to Shaoxing. Zhu Yun, WJ, 13.259-262, traces the ancestry to the Yin Xian Shi(5) and to a Shi(5) Wei 惟, who moved from Liyang to Yin Xian and then a 9th generation descendant, Changru who moved from Yin Xian to Yuyao during the Yuan. This Shi(5) Wei finds no mention in Richard Davis or elsewhere. Finally, Zhu Yun, WJ, 13.257-259, Traces moves from Liyang to Yin Xian to Yuyao and then a subsequent move to Shanyin, but does not mention Changru. We are sticking with Changru as the 13th generation ancestor of Zaibian [29967], father of the four brothers who moved to Wanping and also sticking with Yuyao as the ancestral address.

Leng(1) Heshu [19543] He is listed in Nanchang FZ, 29.17a as a Yuan dynasty, Zhiyuan 5 jinshi (cyclical year=guiwei). Neither earlier nor later Zhiyuan 5 was a guiwei year. Moreover, neither was a jinshi year. Jiangxi TZ and its source lists him as a Zhzheng 2, renwu cyclical year jinshi, but Nanchang FZ rejects this dating. A grandson of Yingcheng [19538], Jingxian [19544], is listed as a Dade 2 jinshi (1298), but no jinshi sitting in this year either. The Yuan jinshi begin with the 1315 sitting. The TZ preface to the Yuan listings cite Qian(1) Daxin's (not in dataset) conclusions that the Yuan listings are all garbled, which clearly seems to be the case here. I am arbitrarily making Heshu a jinshi by grace at the end of his career in 1283, and Jingxian as a 1315 jinshi, which is the only guess that makes any kind of chronological logic. The only more or less firm conclusion is that both Heshu and Jingxian received some kind of degree under Yuan and that both probably had civil service careers.
